Here’s a cleaned and structured version of the discussion.

What the discussion was mainly about

The team is trying to move EKS-related Terraform deployments away from the old IAM user + assume-role pattern and toward OIDC-based authentication for Terraform Cloud/private runners.

Right now, deployment still depends on elevated access in some places, and that is not acceptable for rollout to consumer accounts. So before this can be broadly launched, a new role and access model must be set up correctly in each consumer account.

⸻

Core technical discussion

1. Current problem

Today, deployment is being done using a higher-privileged role, but consumer accounts do not have that same access model.

The existing cluster access role is read-only in some accounts, so it cannot launch the Service Catalog product. That means rollout is blocked until a proper deployment role is created with the required permissions.

2. Dependency identified

Before rollout, each EKS/consumer account needs:
	•	a new role with the right permissions for Service Catalog launch
	•	access entry updates so the new OIDC role can actually operate against the cluster
	•	integration updates so the Service Catalog side knows which role to use

This was clearly called out as a prerequisite.

3. Terraform/module changes being proposed

The module is being updated so it no longer relies on the old assume-role flow.

That means:
	•	removing old assume-role references from Terraform code
	•	removing variables related to that pattern
	•	relying on workspace/environment authentication instead
	•	updating wrapper configs and templates as well, not just the shared module

This is important: the change is not only in one module. It affects:
	•	wrapper module
	•	cluster-specific wrapper configs
	•	Bitbucket/Jenkins templates
	•	workspace/project setup in Terraform Cloud

4. Big concern raised: local-exec / kubectl flows

A very important question was raised around places where local-exec or kubectl commands depend on exported AWS credentials.

That matters because previously:
	•	Terraform Cloud had IAM user credentials
	•	pipeline used STS assume-role
	•	temporary credentials were exported
	•	kubectl/local-exec commands used those exported credentials

Now with OIDC, the team needs to confirm:
	•	whether those credentials are still available in a usable form
	•	whether they refresh automatically
	•	whether long-running operations will break
	•	whether local-exec/kubectl patterns still work the same way

This is one of the biggest technical risks from the discussion.

⸻

Migration approach being debated

Two possible approaches were discussed.

Option A: Do migration during Argo CD rollout or upgrade

The idea here is:
	•	when touching a cluster anyway for Argo CD or upgrade
	•	also migrate its workspace/project/module/auth pattern at the same time

The benefit:
	•	testing happens naturally during a real plan/apply
	•	avoids doing a separate Terraform apply window just for migration

The downside:
	•	too many moving parts in one change window
	•	harder to troubleshoot if something breaks
	•	rollback becomes more complicated because multiple things changed at once

Option B: Separate activity before larger operations

The safer view from others was:
	•	keep Argo CD and upgrade changes as simple as possible
	•	test OIDC migration separately
	•	use lab/test/new clusters first
	•	build confidence before using it in large upgrade windows

This view got strong support because the upcoming upgrade already has a lot of complexity.

⸻

Important operational concerns raised

1. This is not “just one manual change”

Dan pointed out that even if one step feels small, it becomes large when multiplied across many clusters and workspaces.

This is a strong engineering point:
	•	one manual step × many clusters = operational risk
	•	repeated manual moves increase chance of inconsistency or human error

2. Rollback is not simple

Rollback is not only “move workspace back.”

Because once you:
	•	move workspace to new project
	•	remove old credentials
	•	update module/wrapper code

then rollback may require both:
	•	workspace/project rollback
	•	code/module rollback

That makes rollback planning essential.

3. Bulk migration vs workspace-by-workspace

Bulk variable updates/API-driven changes are technically possible, but the team is worried that:
	•	they do not provide enough validation
	•	they do not prove end-to-end success
	•	they create risk without good testing checkpoints

So the preferred model seems closer to:
	•	test in lab
	•	test on new cluster(s)
	•	possibly move workspace-by-workspace
	•	validate end-to-end plan/apply

⸻

Authentication/session duration discussion

There was also a detailed discussion about why credentials used to expire.

Old pattern

Previously:
	•	Terraform used short-lived credentials
	•	local kubectl commands reused those same credentials
	•	if those expired during long operations, commands failed

To fix that, the team explicitly generated temporary credentials using STS assume-role and exported them.

New OIDC question

Now the open question is:
	•	with OIDC, what is the actual session duration?
	•	does Terraform refresh credentials automatically?
	•	do local-exec/kubectl steps still fail if they reuse temporary values without refresh?

Important technical conclusion from Dan:
	•	Terraform provider can refresh credentials when making AWS API calls
	•	but kubectl/local-exec may not automatically refresh in the same way
	•	so the problem is not Terraform alone, but anything outside Terraform that directly reuses credentials

That is exactly why this needs validation before rollout.

⸻

New cluster idea

A practical idea came up:
use new clusters as a safer place to introduce this model first.

Why this is a good idea:
	•	no legacy workload dependency
	•	easier to test new project/workspace/OIDC setup
	•	lower migration complexity than existing clusters
	•	gives confidence before touching existing fleet

That is probably the best pilot path from this discussion.

⸻

Suggested cleaned meeting outcome

Decisions leaning toward agreement
	1.	OIDC migration is needed.
	2.	Consumer rollout is blocked until the new required role/access model exists.
	3.	This change affects module code, wrapper code, workspace/project setup, and templates.
	4.	Local-exec/kubectl credential behavior must be validated before rollout.
	5.	Doing this inside a large upgrade/change window is risky unless tested first.
	6.	Lab clusters and new clusters are the best places to validate first.

⸻

