	•	Review documentation and technical change set.
	•	Think through communication plan for pilot teams if this change is included.

Team / Dan / broader group
	•	Decide whether migration is:
	•	separate pre-work, or
	•	part of a controlled pilot only
	•	Define rollback plan clearly
	•	Decide who gets temporary workspace/project migration permissions
	•	Evaluate whether new cluster provisioning should use OIDC model first

⸻

Risks

Technical risks
	•	local-exec/kubectl may fail if credentials expire
	•	missing permissions in new role/access entry setup
	•	wrapper/template changes missed in some places
	•	hidden dependency on old assume-role pattern

Operational risks
	•	too many changes in same change window
	•	difficult rollback
	•	repeated manual workspace movement
	•	vacation/ownership gap if the work is not handed off clearly

⸻

My read as a senior engineer

The safest path is:
	1.	finish lab validation first
	2.	confirm credential/session behavior for local-exec and kubectl
	3.	release a beta module from feature branch
	4.	test on one or two new/internal clusters
	5.	document exact migration steps and rollback
	6.	only then decide whether it should be included near Argo or upgrades

Why this path is better:
	•	it isolates the authentication change
	•	it gives real evidence instead of assumptions
	•	it reduces blame confusion during Argo or upgrade failures
	•	it gives a repeatable rollout model for the rest of the fleet
